The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Nation Briefs
                                                                                                                 NATION BRIEFS
                                      
	 London, Oct. 16 (PTI): An Indian-born barrister in the UK has accused the head of chambers of the Four New Square bar association and his legal clerks of racial discrimination and has demanded 33 million in damages.           
	Aisha Bijlani claimed the accused had conspired to stop her from receiving high-profile and lucrative assignments on the grounds of her race and origin.                   
	 Thiruvananthapuram (PTI): The State Bank of India has withdrawn a 30-year-old norm that places restrictions on granting immediate postings to pregnant women after recruitment.                   
	 Mumbai (PTI): Air India will operate 137 special flights for Haj pilgrims travelling to Jeddah and Medina from October 20. The national carrier will also operate 117 flights to connect passengers to special Haj flights of Saudi Arabian Airlines and NAS Air.                  
	 Mumbai (PTI): Bombay High Court on Thursday dismissed a public interest litigation challenging the extension granted to Anil Kakodkar, the chairman of the Atomic Energy Commission. A former Bhabha Atomic Research Centre employee had filed the PIL saying Kakodkar had already been given four extensions and a fifth was a violation of statutory provisions.                   
	 Mumbai (PTI): Bombay High Court on Friday asked the CBI to investigate the death of a man in custody and ordered that a murder case be filed against three police officers. Altaf Shaikh, 22 died in custody a day after he was arrested in a house break-in case. The police said he died of drug overdose but the post-mortem report said there were several injury marks on his body.                  
	 Bulandshahr (PTI): Two youths were killed and 12 suffered burn injuries after a fire broke out in Shikarpur cracker market in Uttar Pradeshs Bulandshahr district. About 40 shops were gutted and goods worth Rs 1 crore destroyed.                                                                                                                           
